# Our Relationship With AI

**Author: Adit Rada**  
**Last Updated: Jun 6, 2025**  

**Note:** This article is an **hypothesis**, not a theory.

# 1\. Introduction

As AI chatbots become more prevalent and as AI agents emerge, the human relationship with AI has increasingly come into the forefront. This drives us to ask a number of questions. What does it mean to have an AI friend? Will an AI assistant be a drop-in replacement for a human assistant? Looking slightly farther ahead, how can AI agents and humanoid robots fit into human society? Will the integration be seamless?

The more we dig into these questions, the more we begin to poke at one of the human brain’s most impressive feats. The ability that has been, in some ways, the hardest to reverse engineer in modern AI systems. This is the ability of Theory of Mind (ToM), which is so embedded in our subconscious, that we take it for granted. However, it is the foundation on which human societies and civilizations have been built on. It may be the understated hero in our ability to have social lives.

In this article, we discuss Theory of Mind and AI. What is Theory of Mind? Why did it evolve? Why is it useful? How does it work? Will it work with AI?

# 2\. What is Theory of Mind?

**Theory of Mind (ToM)** is the act of inferring someone’s *intent* and *knowledge.* It is so named because it requires having a theory about the mind of others \[[1](https://www.google.com/books/edition/A_Brief_History_of_Intelligence/tymCEAAAQBAJ?hl=en)\].

Let’s consider two examples, each to illustrate inferring intent and knowledge of someone else.

* Consider the following study to infer someone’s intent \[[2](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15484596/)\]. Have a chimpanzee sit across from two experimenters who have food near them. Experimenter A *intends to give food but is unable* to give food for various reasons (sometimes unable to see the food; sometimes the food is stuck; other times they demonstrate losing the food). On the other hand, experimenter B *does not have the intention* to give food (simply having the food around but unwilling to give it). At the end, neither experimenter gave food to the chimpanzee. However, the chimpanzee treats these two cases very differently. When given the chance to pick between the two experimenters, the chimpanzee always went back to experimenter A. This means that the chimpanzee was able to use cues about the situation of another person to *infer the intent*, and thereby predict the likelihood this other person would give them food in the future.  
* Now, let’s consider an example of inferring someone’s knowledge \[[4](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31570582/)\]. Here, chimpanzees were given the chance to play with two sets of goggles \- one was transparent and another was opaque. When given the chance to ask for food from two human experimenters wearing those goggles, the chimpanzee went to the human that was wearing transparent goggles. This means that the chimpanzee could infer the *knowledge* of each experimenter and could tell the person wearing the opaque glasses wouldn’t see them.

In day-to-day human interactions, Theory of Mind is so prevalent that we don’t even notice it. For example, a friend at a party keeps glancing at their watch and moving towards the door; we can easily infer their intent to leave. It can be hard to both explain and understand ToM, especially when compared to other abilities, say vision. It is so embedded in our subconscious that the abilities it gives seem obvious. As a thought experiment of how it would be to not have ToM, imagine walking into a workplace and you see people doing actions but you are not able to understand their intentions. For example, you see someone walk to the kitchen with an empty bottle but not know why. You would see someone jog to a meeting room and not understand that they are running late, and so on.

In the human lineage, the ability to engage in Theory of Mind first emerged in early primates 15 million years ago. The ability was not present in early mammals. Even dogs, as socially intelligent and attentive to humans as they are, may be unable to understand that humans can hold different knowledge \[[4](https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/j.1467-7687.2009.00815.x)\]. Allow a dog to see its trainer put a treat at location A and then allow the dog to see someone else put a treat in a different location B while the trainer is not present and hence unaware of the treat at location B. When the trainer comes back and commands “get the treat”, dogs are equally likely to run to either location, failing to identify the location the trainer is referring to based on which location the trainer has knowledge about.

We now know what Theory of Mind is and saw that it first emerged in early primates. The question to now ask is why did it emerge? What were the conditions that led evolution to hone in on this feature?

# 3\. Why did Theory of Mind evolve?

Primates (which humans are a part of) are a social species that live in groups. Any social species or group has a social hierarchy, this is true of species as diverse as camels, lions, elephants, and primates. However, what makes primate societies unique is not the presence of a social hierarchy, but how the hierarchy is constructed. If we examined the social hierarchy of different primate groups, we would notice that it often isn’t the strongest, biggest, or most aggressive monkey who sits at the top. For most other social animals, physical strength is the sole determinant of rank in the social hierarchy. For primates, though, it is not only *physical* power that determines one’s social ranking but also *political* power.

As is the case in human civilizations, one thing that determines a monkey’s rank is the family it is born into. A weak and frail juvenile member of a powerful family can easily scare off a much larger and stronger adult monkey from a family that ranks below her. The second thing that determines the social rank is the ability of the monkey to forge friendships and play politics. Like human societies \- with endless oscillations of dynastic power struggles of families rising and falling \- monkey dynasties rise and fall too \[[5](https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/BF02383139)\]. Families face incredible pressure to improve their position as high ranking members get their pick of food, resting sites, and mates, thus improving their odds of survival and their genes being passed on \[[6](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/14615543/)\]. To maintain their social rank, or climb up the ladder, monkeys often forge alliances with nonfamily members. Studies have shown that higher ranking monkeys are the ones that are better at recruiting allies from non-blood related individuals \[[7](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31968874/)\]. Primate politics happens in the dynamics of these allyships, which are forged not through fixed familial relationships but by forming friendships.

Much of monkey’s social behavior suggests an incredible degree of political forethought. Monkeys prefer to invest in relationships with those ranked higher than themselves. Monkeys prefer to mate with high ranking members of the group. Monkeys compete to groom with high ranking individuals. When a dispute breaks out, monkeys are biased toward joining forces with higher ranking individuals. The children of high ranking mothers are the most popular playmates.

So, how are politics and Theory of Mind related? The political savviness required to climb up the social hierarchy is *enabled* by Theory of Mind. Only with Theory of Mind can individuals infer what others want and thereby figure out whom to cozy up to and how. Only through ToM can individual primates know not to mess with a low ranking individual with high ranking friends; this requires *understanding the intent* of the high ranking individuals and what they will do in future situations. Only through the ability of ToM can one figure out who is likely to become powerful in the future, whom to make friends with, and whom to deceive.

## 3.1 Environmental Conditions That Led to ToM

Okay, we have just gone through why ToM first emerged: it enabled one to climb up a social hierarchy with politicking instead of physical power. But this begs the question of what unique environmental niche put pressure on evolution to develop this ability.

Early primates found themselves in unique conditions in the aftermath of the Permian Triassic extinction event (a.k.a the asteroid blowing the dinosaurs up). Early primates seemed to have had a unique diet of foraging fruits directly in treetops \- they were frugivores. They plucked fruit from the trees right after it ripened but before it fell to the forest floor. This allowed early primates to have easy access to food without much competition from other species. This unique ecological environment gave early primates two gifts:

1) Calories: easy access to fruit gave them an abundance of calories providing them the evolutionary option to spend energy on bigger brains.  
2) Time: free time is extremely rare in the animal kingdom, daily calendars are filled up with eating, mating, and resting \[[8](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19575315/)\]. But these frugivorous primates didn’t have to spend nearly as much time foraging as other animals did, so when seeking to climb up the social hierarchy, these primates had a new evolutionary option: instead of spending time growing bigger muscles to fight their way to the top, they could spend time to politick their way to the top. Evolution chose the latter option.

This created a completely new evolutionary arms race: a battle for the political savvy. Any primate born with better ToM skills would be better at currying favor and gaining allies, and would thus survive better and have more babies. This put more pressure on other primates to evolve better Theory of Mind skills for smarter politicking. An outgrowth of this arms race seems to have been a blossoming of many human social instincts, both the good (friendship, reciprocity, reconciliation, trust, sharing) and the bad (tribalism, nepotism, deception),

Before we continue, let’s step back and appreciate the moment in time and space we are currently in. The fluke of evolution is incredibly magical. What about the counterfactual if evolution did not decide to choose politicking as a way to climb social hierarchies and stuck with muscle power. Would we have had the world wars? Would we have had the societies we have today? This is another “what if” question that we will not have a satisfying answer to.

## 3.2 Theory of Mind and Humans

Humans inherited ToM from early primates. This gift enabled two major things: communication and societies.

### 3.2.1 Communication

Let’s start with communication (which is primarily done via language in humans). When humans use language with each other, there is an ungodly number of assumptions made that are not found in the words themselves. We *infer* what people actually mean by what they say. Humans can easily infer that when someone asks us to “maximize paperclip production”, that person does not mean to convert Earth and the Universe into paperclips. This seemingly obvious inference is actually powered by Theory of Mind. It is only via ToM can we *infer* the implicit instructions within the explicit spoken words. 

Consider another example presented by linguist Steven Pinker:  
*Bob: I am leaving you.*  
*Alice: Who is she?*  
If we heard this, we would easily *infer* that Bob is breaking up with Alice for another woman. The ability powering and enabling this inference is Theory of Mind. We (subconsciously) render a simulation of another mind to explore different scenarios and hone in on the most likely scenario.

The intertwining of Theory of Mind and language is ubiquitous. Every conservation is built on top of the foundation of Theory of Mind \- inferring what one means by what he said and inferring what should be said to maximize the chance the other knows what we mean.

The relationship between Theory of Mind and language can even be seen in the architecture of the brain. Wernicke’s area, presumably the place where words are learned and stored, is right in the middle of the neocortical regions responsible for Theory of Mind. Indeed, the temporoparietal junction, which is highly selective for modeling other people’s intentions and knowledge, is entirely overlapping with Wernicke’s area \- which is required for people to understand speech.

### 3.2.2 Complex Societies

Theory of Mind played a pivotal role in enabling the development of complex and stable human societies. Without it, human societies would likely resemble those of other social animals \- perhaps organized into small, relatively simple groups, but lacking the intricate structures, cooperation, and cultural depth we observe.

ToM enables complex societies in many ways. But the two major ways are cooperation, and teaching. Firstly, ToM enables humans to cooperate and collaborate at a large scale. Complex cooperative tasks like agriculture require individuals to understand not just their own actions but also intentions and goals of others in the group. ToM allows us to infer that everyone is working towards a common objective, even if their individual actions are different. ToM is also essential for trust, reciprocity, and empathy. We infer whether someone is trustworthy by understanding their past intentions and predicting future behavior. This ability to assess others’ reliability is foundational for reciprocal altruism and large-scale cooperation among non-kin. Without ToM, cooperation would be rudimentary and based purely on immediate observable cures. Individuals might coordinate to chase a deer, but the complex sustained cooperation among non-kin required for agriculture, raising children in a shared community would be absent. There would be no shared understanding of future goals or long-term commitments.

Secondly, ToM enables teaching. This is as teaching involves understanding what the learner knows, what they need to learn, and how to convey that information. This consequently enables passing down knowledge across generations and enables future generations to build on top \- enabling one to stand on the shoulders of giants.

In summary, without ToM, human interaction would be reduced to a series of reactive, surface-level exchanges. The rich tapestry of shared beliefs, complex social contracts, moral frameworks (good and bad), and cultural narratives that define human societies simply could not emerge or evolve. ToM is the cognitive glue that binds us into incredibly complex social structures.

Note: Just because humans have the ability of Theory of Mind does not mean that we are necessarily good at it. Both from history and personal experience, we can attest to the fact that humans often misunderstand each other. But, something is better than nothing.

## 3.3 Consciousness

Let’s go on a slight digression. Theory of Mind may also be the locus of consciousness. The definition of **consciousness** that I use is self-awareness, a.k.a thinking about oneself, a.k.a, thinking about thinking, a.k.a metacognition.

Perhaps the mechanism by which consciousness emerges is the same mechanism by which we engage in Theory of Mind: the ability to infer the intent of a mind can be used for any mind \- whether it’s the mind of the person opposite to you, or your own mind. *Consciousness is theory of mind for your own mind*.

Consider this example. With ToM, we can correctly infer the cravings of someone deprived of food (“How hungry would Bob be if he didn’t eat for 24h?”) even though we ourselves might not be hungry, perhaps too with ToM, we can infer the intent our own mind in a future situation (“How hungry would I be if I didn’t eat for 24h?”) even though we are currently not hungry. This is consciousness in action\! You are thinking about yourself. Thus, consciousness first emerged in early primates and was passed onto humans.

Up till now, we have gone through why ToM first evolved and what benefits it yielded. With this info, one might think that today’s LLMs can also understand the intent and knowledge of others. While on the surface it might appear as so, it’s only when we dig into *how* ToM works in primate brains can we begin to answer the question whether AI ToM is real or just an illusion.

# 4\. How Does Theory of Mind Work?

To learn about how ToM works, we need to build our trunk of knowledge step-by-step. To be able to model the mind of someone else, we need to at least be able to model our own mind. Therefore, let’s start with learning how we model our own mind.

## 4.1 Modeling Oneself

The new brain regions that emerged in early primates were the granular prefrontal cortex (gPFC), superior temporal sulcus (STS), and the temporoparietal junction (TPJ). These regions become uniquely active in tasks that require self-reference such as evaluating your own personality traits, general self-related mind wandering, considering *your* own feelings, thinking about *your* own intentions, and thinking about *yourself* in general \[[9](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19433790/), [10](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20045475/)\]. People with damage to the gPFC develop mirror-sign syndrome where they can not recognize *themselves* in the mirror.

On the other hand, mammals like rats without the gPFC can’t think about themselves. They can think about the world, e.g. “there’s water to the left”, but they can’t imagine themselves in their mental simulations. Primates, on the other hand, can think about themselves and can say “*I* am thirsty, and *I* know there’s water to the left so *I* will go there”. Notice the “I”, that is self-reference.

These together suggest that the gPFC, and TPJ construct a model of oneself, i.e., one’s *own intentions and knowledge*. They enable metacognition. Thinking about thinking.

* Primates with gPFC and TPJ: “Because I am hungry \[self-reference & knowledge\], eating feels good when I am hungry, and to the best of my knowledge going to the left leads to food, so I’ll go to the left \[intent\]”.  
* Mammals without gPFC and TPJ: “Left leads to food”. Notice that while this is knowledge that the mammal knows, it differs from primates who create a model of the knowledge itself, i.e., *why* does that knowledge exist in the first place. E.g. “Because the last time *I* went over there, *I* saw water, and hence when *I* simulate going to the left, *I* see water in my imagination.”

So, how do we model our own mind \- the gPFC & TPJ build a model of our own intentions and knowledge. A **model** is anything that predicts what will likely come next, e.g. a language model predicts what’s the likely next word. Okay, now that we’ve looked on to how we model our own mind, we can see how we model other minds.

## 4.2 Modeling Other Minds

Consider the classic false-belief test called the Sally-Anne test below:  
![][image1]

Answering this test correctly requires you to know Sally's knowledge and know that it is different from your own. This is Theory of Mind\! The gPFC activates during such tasks \[[11](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/11259662/)\], i.e. when inferring other people’s intent and knowledge. This suggests that the gPFC & TPJ play a major role in modeling other minds, i.e., in understanding others.

In addition, people with gPFC damage are much worse at recognizing emotion in others, empathizing, and deceiving. On the other hand, the bigger the gPFC, the higher in the social hierarchy a primate tends to be and the larger his or her social network.

### 4.2.1 Modeling Your Mind to Model Other Minds

The following picture summarizes what we have learned so far:

The fact that *both modeling your own mind and modeling other minds* happens in the gPFC & TPJ is quite telling\! One has to wonder why?

**Social projection theory** proposes that the way we infer the intent of someone else is by imaging ourselves in their situation. ***This is why the gPFC is used for both understanding oneself and others***. For example, “She yelled at me because she is running late, I would also yell if I was running late since I would be anxious”. Notice how one imagines themselves in another's shoes to understand the other person. As a second example, being in a specific mood (e.g. happy, sad or hungry) makes you more biased to inaccurately assume that others are in that state too. This intertwining of your own internal state and others suggests that the same gPFC is used for both and provides more evidence to social projection theory.

**Mirror Neurons**  
In addition to the gPFC, mirror neurons provide more evidence to the fact that we understand others by imagining ourselves in their situation. **Mirror neurons** are a class of neurons in primates that activate ***both*** when an individual performs a specific action and when they observe someone else perform the same action. They are so named because of their mirror-like behavior.

One interpretation of this is that mirror neurons are evidence that primates (subconsciously) imagine themselves doing what they see someone else doing. Doing this may help them understand other’s intentions, i.e., *why* they are doing what they are doing.

Let’s consider two examples:

* Action understanding: By activating the same neural circuits involved in the other person performing the action, the observer essentially simulates the action in their own brain. This can help the observer understand what the other individual is doing. For example, picking up a box. The mirror neurons in the observer for being in a posture to pick up the box also activate, enabling the observer to understand the intent of the action. Studies show that by temporarily inhibiting mirror neurons, the observer can no longer infer the weight of the box by observing the stance of the person picking it up.  
* Intent recognition: For example different mirror neurons may fire if a monkey observes a hand grasping a peanut with the intention to eat vs the intention to throw.

Note that these mirror neuron activations happen subconsciously and automatically. You can’t choose not to do it.

People with impairments in performing specific movements also show impairments in understanding the intentions of those very same movements. For example, someone unable to brush their own teeth struggle to recognize teeth-brushing in others.

So in conclusion, how does Theory of Mind work? *We infer the knowledge and intent of others, i.e., understand others by imagining ourselves in their situation*. Our earlier picture actually turns out to be this:

## 4.3 Inductive Bias of gPFC, TPJ, & Mirror Neurons

If you have ever gone on a wildlife safari, or walked in the zoo, or seen a National Geographic documentary, you would have noticed that you find the chimps and baboons much more relatable than buffaloes or antelopes. That is, you are able to understand the chimp much better than the rest of the animals. Why is this? To answer this question we need to learn about inductive biases and how the neural hardware (gPFC, TPJ) that enables ToM may have a certain inductive bias.

In the context of machine learning, an **inductive bias** is an assumption made by the learning algorithm by virtue of how it is designed. For example, for computer vision we use convolutional neural networks that (unlike feed forward neural networks) have an inductive bias of translation invariance. That is, a given object in one corner of the image should be recognized in the same way as when the same object is in the opposite corner of the image. This is an impregnable fact of our visual world: the same thing (say a table) can exist in two different places (e.g. to the left or to the right) without the thing being different. Thus, instead of a vanilla neural network trying to learn this fact of translational invariance, we simply hardcode it into the architecture, giving us CNNs.

**Hypothesis:** It is plausible that the way gPFC, TPJ, & mirror neurons enable ToM may rely on an inductive bias. That bias is the assumption of a shared or highly similar underlying neural architecture and processing.

The core idea of how ToM works is that we understand others by simulating ourselves in their situation. This is done using the neural hardware of gPFC, TPJ, and mirror neurons. For this simulation to be effective and accurate, the “software” being simulated needs to be relatively compatible with the “hardware” it’s running on. That is, the closer the neural architecture between you and the individual you are trying to understand, the better you will be able to understand that individual.

For example, if your mirror neurons fire when you see someone reaching for a cup, it’s because your brain has pre-existing neural pathways for “reaching for a cup”. The assumption is that your brain has similar, if not identical neural primitives for that action. If their “reach” was fundamentally different at a neural level (say they reached with their toes, or through some completely alien mechanism that you couldn’t possibly do), then you won’t have mirror neurons for performing that action and thus won’t be able to understand what they are doing.

Let’s consider chimps and dogs as examples. Humans and chimps share a very recent common ancestor and have highly similar brain structures. Therefore, our gPFC, TPJ, and mirror neurons have a high degree of overlap or compatibility when observing each other. The degree of similarity between a human and a monkey brain is higher than that between a human and a dog brain. When a human observes a monkey slyly walking behind another monkey who has food, the human neurons for that same behavior would light up because the brains are structurally similar. This allows that human to understand the intentions of the monkey, as the human is more easily able to simulate themselves in the monkey’s situation.

![][image2]  
This level of understanding differs with dogs. While humans can certainly understand a great deal about dogs (their emotions, some intentions, and their wants), this understanding is largely inferential and less “direct” or “simulated” compared to understanding another monkey.

A dog’s motor programs, communication signals (barking, tail wagging, ear positions), and other emotional expressions are generated by neural circuits that are distinct from ours. When a dog wags its tail, a human might *interpret* it as happiness, but it does not directly activate the same neural pathways in the human that produce tail wagging. Thus, we can’t subconsciously simulate ourselves in the dog's position. Consequently, we can’t understand the dog, we instead learn an association that “tail wagging \= happiness”.

The fact that we find monkeys more relatable than dogs might prove the case that an inductive bias exists in our gPFC and mirror neurons. The gPFC may have a built-in assumption that the observed agent’s internal states and actions are generated by neural processes similar to one’s own. The more similar the two neural systems are, the more accurate and effortless the social projection and subsequent Theory of Mind can be.

This may also be why it’s much easier for us to understand close friends and family members (because your neural structures are similar due to sharing more experiences together \[[12](https://www.google.com/books/edition/Why_We_Remember/_ZEuEQAAQBAJ?hl=en)\]), than it is to understand a stranger human. But also, we can understand a stranger human much more than we can understand a chimp (a primate) who we can understand better than a dog (a mammal) who we can understand more than an alligator (a reptile), and so on.

# 5\. What Now With AI and Robots?

So, we have gone through what Theory of Mind is, why it is the cornerstone on which human society is built on, and how it works at a biological level. The main takeaway is that we understand others by simulating ourselves (subconsciously and automatically) in their situation. This simulation likely relies on the inductive bias that the simulation assumes a shared or sufficiently similar architecture.

As we prepare for a *potential* future where AI agents and humanoid robots seamlessly integrate into human society, this inductive bias may be a stumbling problem to solve in order for Theory of Mind to continue to work with AI agents \- both for humans to understand robots, and for robots to understand humans.

## 5.1 Problem

The primary problem is that the inductive bias made by gPFC, TPJ, and mirror neurons (which enable social projection for ToM) no longer holds. Imagine trying to understand an AI agent embodied in a humanoid robot, because the same neural hardware is not shared, we may not be able to *accurately* simulate ourselves in their situation, and thus not understand them, and thus no ToM. But, since human societies are built on the foundation of ToM, not being able to use ToM on AI agents may: A) prevent seamless integration of AI into human societies (the AI would still be a useful tool though); or B) the integration would be unstable.

Two humans talking to each other are running on the *same* neural substrate, so the implicit assumptions made for social projection hold. But with AI agents, they are running on different hardware than humans. Thus, even if the AI agent exhibits the same behavior, and says the same things, it doesn’t necessarily mean that this sensation of consciousness that we humans have is the same that the AI agent will have \[[13](https://www.cbsnews.com/news/artificial-intelligence-google-deepmind-ceo-demis-hassabis-60-minutes-transcript/#:~:text=Demis%20Hassabis%3A%20I%20think,thing%20they%20will%20have.)\].

A secondary (and maybe more dangerous) problem is the *illusion* of Theory of Mind between humans and AI agents, that is we think we understand them when we actually don’t. LLMs are incredibly good at modeling and mimicking human language and responding in ways that *appear* insightful, empathetic, or knowledgeable. This is because they have been trained on a colossal amount of human generated text, which reflects our expressions of understanding, emotion, and intent.

As humans, we may be wired to detect agency and attribute mental states to anything that resembles human-behavior. When an LLM generates coherent and contextually relevant text, our natural tendency is to infer that it “understands” us. However, this illusion of understanding can lead to dangerous scenarios like misplaced trust. This may have been the case when a teenager’s mental health may have been influenced by his chats with AI \[[14](https://www.nbcnews.com/tech/characterai-lawsuit-florida-teen-death-rcna176791), [21](https://www.nature.com/articles/s42256-025-01051-5)\]. It is better to know that something does not work, than to believe that something works when it actually does not work.

## 5.2 Consequences

It is hard to say that *if* ToM with AI is actually a problem, what then will be the consequences. Nevertheless, we can still paint one of many possible scenarios.

Nick Bostrom’s famous paperclip problem \[[15](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Instrumental_convergence)\] illustrates Theory of Mind with AI agents not working. Here, an AI agent is given the task of “maximizing paperclip production” at a factory. The AI agent starts out with optimizing production processes at the factory, but then starts expanding and building new factories, diverting energy sources from humans to paperclip production. Eventually, killing humans, converting Earth and the rest of the Universe into paperclips. This can only happen because the AI agent was unable to use Theory of Mind to understand the intentions of the human. As we already saw in section 3.2.1, communication relies on a huge number of implicit assumptions that are powered by Theory of Mind.

Now, let’s consider how AI robots integrating into human society may play out \[[16](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Machines_Like_Me)\]. Without Theory of MInd, the agents will be ill-equipped to understand human decision making, the way our principles are warped in the force field of our emotions, our peculiar biases, our self-delusion, and all the defects of our cognition.

One proposed solution to this has been AI specifications like Anthropic’s Claude Constitution \[[17](https://www.anthropic.com/news/claudes-constitution)\]. These specifications are hardcoded rules on how the AI should behave when interacting with humans, aimed to ensure AI’s integrate seamlessly into human societies. I am skeptical that these AI specifications are a scalable and sustainable solution to the problem. Primates are not born with rules that tell them how to behave and interact with other primates. Instead they are born with an architecture and an algorithm (gPfc, TPJ, mirror neurons) that enables Theory of Mind which then allows them to understand others and *learn* how to interact with others.

Over the last two decades, we have also learned the same lesson in AI: learning systems always beat hardcoded rules. That is the message of Richard Sutton’s “The Bitter Lesson” \[[18](https://www.cs.utexas.edu/~eunsol/courses/data/bitter_lesson.pdf)\]. It is the reason why AlphaZero \- a learning system \- went on to achieve superhuman status. Hardcoded rules or human heuristics on how to play Go would not have taken us all the way \[[19](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hHooQmmzG4k)\]. Therefore, the same principle of learning should also be applied when teaching the AI how to behave with humans.

To further illustrate the problem with AI specification, let’s consider a concrete example. How about a prohibition against lying? According to an AI specification, it’s an abomination. But human social life teems with harmless or even helpful untruths. How do we separate them out? How do we encode the little white lie that spares the blushes of a friend? Or a lie that sends a rapist to prison who would otherwise go free?

An AI agent in human society will find itself in a hurricane of contradictions. We humans have lived with them and the list wearies us. Millions dying of disease we know how to cure. Millions live in poverty when there's enough to go around. We degrade the biosphere when we know it's our only home. We threaten each other with nuclear weapons when we know what it could lead to. We love living things but we permit a mass extinction of species. And all the rest \- genocide, torture, enslavement, school shootings, and scores of daily outrages. We live alongside this torment and aren’t amazed when we still find happiness. Will artificial minds without ToM and only an AI spec instead be able to handle this and integrate seamlessly into our society?

If we want AI agents and robots that can live alongside us, understand the type of people we are, deduce what we don’t know that we want to know, infer what we intend by what we say, anticipate what we need or want before we tell them, navigate social relationships with groups of humans, with all their hidden rules and etiquettes \- in other words, if we want true human like AI agents, then Theory of Mind will undeniably be an essential component of that system.

Solving Theory of Mind also has huge commercial incentives. If AI systems are truly able to infer someone’s intent and knowledge, we could for example deliver hyper-personalized ads that are truly relevant. We could redefine delivering the right ad at the right time. When commercial incentives align with scientific research, progress is usually accelerated.

## 5.3 Solution Paths

So, as of June 2025, what can we do to confront this? Two things to note:

* First, this is a nice problem to have. Just the fact that we are talking about this means we’re tantalizingly close to AGI. If we transport ourselves 10-15 years ago, we would be amazed that this was the problem we are facing given that even training neural networks reliably was challenging.  
* Second, I don’t think this is an unsolvable problem. If you don’t believe that the brain is implementing anything metaphysical (i.e. spirit or soul), then it’s only doing computations. That means, these computations and algorithms can be discovered and replicated in artificial minds as well.

Future directions would be:

* **AI capabilities research**: how can we build Theory of Mind into AI systems. One idea I have had is adding a self-model to MuZero \[[20](https://arxiv.org/pdf/1911.08265)\].  
* **AI safety research**: 1\) research to ensure that an AI agent’s goals and values are aligned with the human designer 2\) AI interpretability research so that neural networks are not black boxes.  
* **Neuroscience research**: if we can understand our own brains better and accurately describe the algorithms that implement ToM, then we can use this knowledge to replicate that in AI.  
* **AI literacy**: Educating the public about how AI works, its abilities, and its lack of abilities like ToM.

The “let’s wait and see” approach is seldom a successful strategy. With technology that is as powerful and transformative as AI, it pays to be proactive rather than reactive.
